title: For Sale/Trade:  Herter's 7mm mag
location: Grays Harbor/ Olympia, Southwest Washington, Washington
postcontent:
Herter's Inc. 7mm mag. Rifle is in good shape, all metal including chamber and bore look great. Marks in the wood but nothing significant. I recently took it completely apart and did a thorough cleaning. I got this gun from an elderly gentleman who said it had not been out of his gunsafe in many years. Says he hunted with it a few times 20+ years ago, he said it shot better than other guns he had that cost 4x as much.  From all the reviews I have read these guns were known as great shooters. 
This Herter's is not associated with the current herter's brand ammo. This gun was manufactured in England in the 1960's by I believe BSA on a mauser action.
A little history I found online: 
Herters sold barreled actions, or complete rifles from 1965 thru 1968 through their mail order catalogue. All Herter's high powered rifles were M98 clones and some were made by companies such as FN or BSA. The gun control act of '68 stopped most sales of firearms via mail order and Herter's retailers with FFLs continued to sell these rifles through about 1970.

 There was an opportunity to buy a barreled action and then a stock made to your taste (type, wood, etc) so as to have at least a semi-custom type rifle. Most of these actions are considered quality types today, so A Herter's rifle in good shape might be a very good to excellent purchase as a shooter. I'd doubt that they would hold any true collector value.

 By the way, George Herter was quite a charactar, selling sporting goods with the best of them through the 50s, 60s and 70s. His typical descriptions of the goods he sold were somewhat over the top, but much of what the company sold was of at least decent quality. He also authored several books, with little to do with his sporting goods business. 

Ok if your not into history, sorry to bore you.  If your looking for a cheap good quality hunting rifle here you go. I would like to get $300 cash firm or $350 trade value. 
Any other firearms would be considered. I could trade up or down, I have cash/ammo/guns for the right trade. You may come to me or a meeting may be arranged in the Olympia/Lacey area.

title: For Sale:  .38 Special +P+ S&W Model 640 {{Hammerless Snubnose}}
postcontent:
This S&W .38 Special Model 640 (no dash) is in good condition, given it’s a quarter century old. It’s 100% mechanically sound, with a solid action, perfect timing/carry-up/lock-up, bright bore & chambers and no rust or serious scratches/gouges. 

Extremely well-suited to CC – no hammer to snag on the draw, no place for lint to accumulate, no worry about putting the gun into SA at the wrong time. Just a smooth, consistent, crisp and safe DAO trigger pull every time. And for anyone that thinks the .38 Special can’t still hold its own, I’d recommend checking out Buffalo Bore’s website to see what the .38 Special can do when loaded to its true potential. In the pocket, in the waistband, in the glove box, on the ankle, on the nightstand…anywhere you’d want to keep a CC gun, these little 640’s are excellent.

It looks like it’s been carried at least a little in its life, but not shot much and definitely not abused. There are some light handling marks throughout the finish of the gun and on the stocks. The stocks are the ones that originally came on this gun back in 1989/1990 and would do fine for CC as they are or could be refinished into looking brand new again…no chips or cracks. This is a 4-digit “CEN” prefix S/N (CEN6xxx), so it was likely about the 6,000th-ish made. Also, as only featured in the first year or so of production; the inside of the frame is marked "TESTED FOR +P+" (S&W's lawyers had this removed early in this model's life). Definitely harder to come by than regular .38 Special 640’s (which aren't all that common to begin with). 

I’m looking to sell this Model 640 for $525, preferably FTF in Everett. Not terribly interested in trades, but would consider offers of S&W revolvers chambered in .22, .38 Special or .357 Magnum made between 1930 & 1996. Will want to see good guy cards. 


Thanks for looking.
